What is Multithreading?

Multithreading is the ability of a program to execute multiple threads concurrently within the same process.

A process is an independent program.
A thread is the smallest unit of execution inside a process.
Threads in the same process share memory (global variables, heap), but each thread has its own stack and program counter.

process vs threads 

| Process                                         | Thread                                            |
| ----------------------------------------------- | ------------------------------------------------- |
| Independent program in execution                | Smallest unit of execution within a process       |
| Has its own memory space                        | Shares the process's memory                       |
| Heavyweight                                     | Lightweight                                       |
| Process creation is expensive                   | Thread creation is cheaper                        |
| Communication is slower (IPC)                   | Communication is faster (shared memory)           |*******VVVVVIMP
| One process crash usually doesn't affect others | A thread crash can terminate the entire process   |
| Each process has its own resources              | Threads share resources like code, data, and heap |


Example

Imagine a web browser:

Thread 1 → UI (responds to clicks)
Thread 2 → Downloads files
Thread 3 → Plays video
Thread 4 → Renders the page

All these threads run concurrently.

Microsoft Word Multithreading Example

Suppose you're typing a document.

While you're typing, several things happen simultaneously:

Thread 1: Handles keyboard input (typing text)
Thread 2: Performs spell checking in the background
Thread 3: Automatically saves the document every few minutes
Thread 4: Updates the UI (cursor blinking, scrolling, menus)

#include <iostream>
#include <thread>

using namespace std;

void task()
{
    cout << "Hello from Worker Thread\n";
}

int main()
{
    cout << "Main Thread Started\n";

    thread t(task);   // Create a new thread

    t.join();         // Wait for worker thread to finish

    cout << "Main Thread Finished\n";

    return 0;
}
